article.headline: Montana 76, Sacramento St. 69
article.story: MISSOULA, Mont. (AP) -- Matt Dlouhy scored 14 points and Jordan Hasquet added 13 points and pulled down 11 rebounds Wednesday to lead Montana to a 76-69 victory over Sacramento State. The Grizzlies (13-11, 7-4) used a balanced scoring attack to make up for the absence of leading scorer Andrew Strait, who was sick and did not dress for the game. Sacramento State (11-14, 3-8) cut the Grizzly lead to 70-69 with one minute left in the game on a layup by Davon Roberts. But Montana put the game away with six straight free throws -- two each by Cameron Rundles, Stuart Mayes and Austin Swift -- in the final 33 seconds. The Hornets led for the first 6 1/2 minutes of the game before Gus Chase tied it for Montana, 11-11, with 13:33 to play. Montana stretched its first-half lead to 10 points, 28-18, when Dlouhy tipped in the ball with 4:20 to play. Sacramento State cut the Grizzly lead to four points, 31-27, on a Kris Groce 3-pointer with 1:16 to go in the half. But Montana took a 36-39 lead to the locker room after Mike Chavez scored with three seconds left in the half. In the second half, Montana took an eight-point lead, 38-30, with 19:19 to play when Hasquet hit two free throws. But the Hornets took the lead, 40-39, with 16:03 left on a dunk by Roderick Adams. Montana regained the lead with 6:21 left, 58-57, on a free throw by Kyle Sharp. The Hornets tied the game again, 62-62, with 4:10 to play on a 3-pointer by Loren Leath. But 10 seconds later, the Grizzlies took the lead for good when Rundles made one of two free throws. Joining Dlouhy and Hasquet in double figures for the Grizzlies were Chase with 12 points and Rundles and Mayes with 11 points each. Kris Groce led the Hornets with 21 points. Alex Bausley chipped in 11.
